Wrote Python script "missingENSG_toHRT_rescue_refseq_ccds_matches.py" on 25.05.26 to check whether the rescue-mapped ENSG entries from the previously unmapped HRT Atlas ENST IDs could be clearly linked back to original HRT Atlas entries.
    Before this step, 35 HRT Atlas ENST IDs were not recovered in the original ENST-to-ENSG BioMart mapping. A rescue mapping via HGNC symbols had recovered 38 ENSG entries, of which 20 were present in the final human all-gene table as non-HK and therefore possible rescue candidates.
    To check these candidates more strictly, the 20 rescue ENSG IDs were used in Ensembl 115 BioMart, Human genes (GRCh38.p14), and exported as "biomart_export_humanHK_rescuemappedENSG_toENST_CCD_RefSeq250526.tsv" on 25.05.26.
    This BioMart export contained the attributes: Gene stable ID, Transcript stable ID, CCDS ID and RefSeq mRNA ID.
    The script uses this BioMart export and compares its RefSeq mRNA IDs and CCDS IDs against the original HRT Atlas file "Housekeeping_GenesHuman_HRTatlas.tsv", which contains ENST ID, Gene.name/HGNC symbol, RefSeq ID and CCDS ID.
    The goal was to avoid adding rescue-mapped genes blindly and to only accept mappings that can be linked unambiguously back to exactly one original HRT Atlas entry.
    The script produced 2 output tables "hrt_atlas_rescue_refseq_ccds_match_check_gene_level.tsv" and "hrt_atlas_rescue_refseq_ccds_match_summary_gene_level.tsv".
    Decision whther to add was made on ENSG/gene level, not on BioMart transcript-row level, because one ENSG can have many transcript, RefSeq or CCDS entries.
    Result: 16 rescue mappings were considered eligible because they matched unambiguously to one original HRT Atlas entry through RefSeq and/or CCDS. 4 rescue candidates were ignored/excluded because they were not sufficiently supported or were not unambiguous.
    This step was therefore useful because it recovered additional HRT Atlas HK genes while keeping the final HK/non-HK assignment conservative and traceable.

