Processed Eisenberg human HK gene list on 31.05.26.
    The original file "eisenberg_hk_genes.tsv" contains 3804 human HK genes from Eisenberg & Levanon 2013, with one column for HGNC gene symbols and one column for RefSeq mRNA accession IDs in the NM_* format.
    The HGNC symbols were used as input in Ensembl 115 BioMart, Human genes (GRCh38.p14), to map the Eisenberg HK genes to Ensembl Gene stable IDs and gene coordinates.
    The BioMart export contained the attributes HGNC symbol, Gene stable ID, Gene start (bp), Gene end (bp), and Chromosome/scaffold name. Its name is "eisenberg_human_hk_gene_lengths_main_chromosomes.tsv"
    BioMart returned more rows than the original 3804 HGNC symbols because some HGNC symbols mapped to multiple Ensembl gene entries, for example due to alternative scaffolds, patches, haplotype regions or duplicated/alternative annotations.
    A Python script was used "Prepare_Eisenberg_HKgenetable.py" to calculate gene_length_bp as Gene end (bp) - Gene start (bp) + 1.
    The script also filtered the table to main chromosomes 1–22, X and Y, excluding MT, patches, alternative scaffolds, haplotype regions and non-standard contigs.
    Duplicate Ensembl Gene stable IDs were removed so that each gene is counted only once for gene-length analysis.
    This produced an Eisenberg HK gene-level table "eisenberg_human_hk_gene_lengths_main_chromosomes.tsv" that can later be compared to the HRT Atlas HK gene set and to the protein-coding human background set.
    Another script was written to create a final table "human_all_genes_with_eisenberg_hk_status.tsv" in which 3502 genes were classified as Eisenberg HK genes and 16582 genes as non-HK genes 
    of the grandtotal which contains all 20084 human protein-coding main-chromosome genes.

Wrote R script "humanHK_eisenberg_genelengthcompare.R" to compare human Eisenberg HK and non-HK gene lengths based on the final human protein-coding main-chromosome background table.
    The script uses "human_all_genes_with_eisenberg_hk_status.tsv", which contains all 20084 human protein-coding main-chromosome genes with calculated gene_length_bp and Eisenberg-based hk_status.
    It creates the summary table "human_eisenberg_gene_length_summary.tsv", containing descriptive statistics for HK and non-HK genes.
    Mean gene length was 48942.80 bp for Eisenberg HK genes and 73532.28 bp for non-HK genes.
    Median gene length was 27784.5 bp for Eisenberg HK genes and 27832.5 bp for non-HK genes.
    The script also creates a log10-scaled boxplot and a mean gene length barplot to visualize the HK vs non-HK comparison.
    A Welch t-test was used to directly compare mean gene lengths between HK and non-HK genes.
    Result: the mean gene length difference was -24589.48 bp, meaning Eisenberg HK genes were on average shorter than non-HK genes.
    The Welch t-test was highly significant with p = 9.00e-54, indicating a statistically significant difference in mean gene length between Eisenberg HK and non-HK genes.

Protein-level HRT Atlas mapping:
    2166/2172 HRT Atlas HK ENSG IDs were mapped to UniProtKB/Swiss-Prot accessions using Uniprot ID Mapping Tool resulting in 2169 Hits. 6 ENSG IDs were not found. 
    Afterwards intersected with the human UniProt Reference Proteome UP000005640_9606 from release 2026_01 using a python script.
    The Human reference proteome contained 20659 protein sequences.
    out of the 2169 Hits 2163 proteins were classified as HK proteins and 18496 proteins as non-HK proteins.
    5 mapped UniProt accessions were not found in the reference proteome FASTA and were documented separately.
    The resulting protein-level table is used for downstream HK vs non-HK protein length comparison.

Wrote R script 02.06.26 "HRTatlas_Human_HK_Protein_Length_stats.R" to analyze protein lengths of human HRT Atlas HK and non-HK proteins.
    The script uses the final protein-level table "human_reference_proteome_with_hrt_atlas_hk_status.tsv", which contains all proteins from the human UniProt Reference Proteome 2026_01 with protein_length_aa and hk_status.
    It creates a summary table with descriptive statistics for HK and non-HK proteins, including n, mean, median, sd, quartiles, IQR, min and max protein length in aa.
    It also creates a log10-scaled boxplot and a mean protein length barplot to visualize HK vs non-HK protein length differences.
    A Wilcoxon rank-sum test was used to test whether the HK and non-HK protein length distributions differ.
    A Welch t-test was used to directly compare mean protein lengths between HK and non-HK proteins.
    Result: 2163 proteins were classified as HRT Atlas HK proteins and 18496 proteins as non-HK proteins.
    Mean protein length was 458 aa for HK proteins and 566 aa for non-HK proteins.
    The Welch t-test showed a significant difference in mean protein length, with HK proteins being shorter on average than non-HK proteins.

Added Welch t-test to the HRT Atlas human gene-length analysis on 03.06.26.
    The Welch t-test was added to the R script for HRT Atlas human gene lengths to directly compare mean gene_length_bp between HK and non-HK genes.
    This was added because the Wilcoxon rank-sum test compares the rank distributions, while the Welch t-test more directly tests whether the mean gene lengths differ between both groups.
    The output table "human_hrt_gene_length_welch_t_test.tsv" was created and stored in the results/tables directory.
    This table contains the test name, comparison, mean HK gene length, mean non-HK gene length, mean difference, test statistic, degrees of freedom, p-value and confidence interval.

